    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_518522569" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/518522569" />
    <a title="Mirjam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7104014-mirjam"><img alt="Mirjam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1529171720p2/7104014.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/518522569?book_show_action=true">Jan 27, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mirjam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mirjam" href="/user/show/7104014-mirjam">Mirjam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer518522569" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4612982403265358123">Think I finished this only because I so believe in Paulo Coehlo. <br/><br/>But I believe less after having waded through this.<br/><br/>I actually like &quot;The Alchemist&quot; less now, see exactly where my buddy was coming from when he told me he didn&apos;t like it because he felt beat over the head with it.<br/><br/>Here, in &quot;Winner&quot; Coehlo gives us an assortment of star-crossed, unwholesome characters who are all supposed to be missing the point in their individual ways as they traverse the glittery nonsense of the Cannes Film Festiv</span>
  <span id="freeText4612982403265358123" style="display:none">Think I finished this only because I so believe in Paulo Coehlo. <br /><br />But I believe less after having waded through this.<br /><br />I actually like "The Alchemist" less now, see exactly where my buddy was coming from when he told me he didn't like it because he felt beat over the head with it.<br /><br />Here, in "Winner" Coehlo gives us an assortment of star-crossed, unwholesome characters who are all supposed to be missing the point in their individual ways as they traverse the glittery nonsense of the Cannes Film Festival. Except with a mysterious/thriller type twist.<br /><br />In theory, that's borderline fantastic. Might've made for an original, substantive, edge-of-one's-seat character study -- if Coehlo had believed in his characters enough to give them real substance.<br /><br />But he hates everyone in this book and he wants you to hate them too, them and their fake surroundings and situation. That's so whether they're young and naive or jaded and sinister, because they're all playing into this money-making, popularity machine he hates so. I went through the story wanting to actually meet the characters -- because it was so obvious the guy telling me about them had an axe to grind that I couldn't take any of his descriptions to heart.<br /><br />The band Tool has a song called, "Learn to Swim," containing lines like: <br /><br />"Some say the end is near.<br />Some say well see armageddon soon.<br />I certainly hope we will cuz<br />I sure could use a vacation from this<br />Silly shit, stupid shit..."<br /><br />Kinda the same idea, coming from a writer who otherwise seemed so interested in affirming life.<br /><br />And that's fine! Coehlo is under no obligation to write positive prose.<br /><br />But he's much better at that. Because "Winner" was so resolutely negative it felt personal, and unprofessionally so. In a poor sport, pouty sort of way that kept him from getting his point across. <br /><br />To be honest, I wouldn't feel comfortable in a setting like Cannes. I'm just not that fabulous. But I'm wary of dismissing anyone who is; I'm not down with considering the entire fashion world and waving off any merit, of suggesting there's no artistic merit whatsoever in movie-making. <br /><br />Certainly, those industries are corrupt (and publishing, not at all?) -- as Coehlo, it feels like, has witnessed more closely than I. But to spit on anyone dreaming of a job in fashion or film, to condemn and dismiss them and their dreams as, in a sense, 'silly, stupid shit...' that bothered me.<br /><br />As did the plot. Which was bad for a bad episode of "Law &amp; Order, SVU." <br /><br />This was an effort to pull back the curtain and provide a pointed critique of an industry(ies) that's got the world fooled -- and I think Coehlo might've been a good guy to do it, if he'd played it delicately and mined his characters for complexities that might've made them quasi-believable. But he laid it on so thick he ruined the attempt. So, in the end, Coehlo wasn't at all a good guy to do it. </span>
  <a data-text-id="4612982403265358123" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

