    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_411317981" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/411317981" />
    <a title="Muhammed" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6751539-muhammed"><img alt="Muhammed" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1366373156p2/6751539.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/411317981?book_show_action=true">Sep 10, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Muhammed" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Muhammed" href="/user/show/6751539-muhammed">Muhammed</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer411317981" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8338383802933758622">This novel is engaging on, rather than criticizing and arguing against the Superclass, discussing examples of individuals from it and &quot;wannabes&quot; of it, as well. Coelho enables the reader to see through the characters&apos; own voice how they suffer to become one of the Superclass, and after becoming so, no one is yet satisfied. If getting invited to attend the festival makes you a Superclass, you are not; a table in a restaurant in Cannes during the Festival makes you from the Superclass, you are not</span>
  <span id="freeText8338383802933758622" style="display:none">This novel is engaging on, rather than criticizing and arguing against the Superclass, discussing examples of individuals from it and "wannabes" of it, as well. Coelho enables the reader to see through the characters' own voice how they suffer to become one of the Superclass, and after becoming so, no one is yet satisfied. If getting invited to attend the festival makes you a Superclass, you are not; a table in a restaurant in Cannes during the Festival makes you from the Superclass, you are not; not until you can get a better table.<br /><br />Coelho's use of the term "Superclass" is just like using Socialist instead of Communist, the word may be overused. The novel is well-open to Marxist criticism.<br /><br />Religion does not play the key role in Coelho's The Winner Stands Alone, except in a spot that includes the whole narrative and that mainly happened years before the novel's Festival took place, exactly when Hamid Hussein's Sheikh advised him not to choose that way and HH disobeys to finally meet his destiny in the very last papers of the novel, remembering his Sheikh's advice. <br /><br />We get to see the Oriental/Bedouin man in Cannes. This duality of a Sadist East vs. a Masochist West is absolutely messed up with, as we, in the Winner Stands Alone, have the East (HH) in a fight, not with the West, but with a further East (Igor). It is like having your sibling in a fight and having to choose your side is very easy, until you know the opponent is your parents.<br /><br />The novel can be thoroughly analyzed in the course of a Feminist critique. However, I do not think something new would emerge except when we have models of fashion being objectified to their age and Ewa's femininity divided between two men with some shades of oriental honor. Therefore, I do not think a feminist critique would bring up something very new.<br /><br />The part where Savoy and the detectives are dealing with the deaths is highly approachable in a Marxist criticism. How all they care for is being famous and solving the cases in which only the rich are victims of, no matter how the poor victims are killed by the same killer as that of the rich is a prominent point.<br /><br />As a whole, I do not like the novel. I was so bored that I opened it once every two or three months to read an extra 50 pages. Paolo could have avoided writing many pages, however, I see he did respectful research and collected some good data which he, apparently, wanted to mention all in this novel. Sometimes, the information was very amusing and presented in an interesting way (like the diamond, guns and the anatomy and how the actress loved the theater). The narration was kind of amusing at sometimes and was boring at many other times. <br /><br />The scene where Hamid attacks Igor trying to take the gun from him is presented in professional way, especially when HH does not know that the Russian ex-husband is not just a mad man holding a gun, but a mad man holding a gun and knowing how to use it professionally, as a man who took part in many wars. The narration here draws to the mind how pathetic HH was when he underestimates his enemy and would urge the reader to think that HH, after he dies, would or would not know that Igor is a professional. The way Coelho described that scene in a slow-motion manner is very expressive and poses many questions on the East and the West, the East and the East, and how the West, even if involuntarily, makes the East kill the East.<br /><br />I had hoped that Coelho would end the novel with the killing scene but the Portuguese could not just hold his pen, did he?<br /><br />Some writers just feel bad about how much information they collected before writing a novel and, even if they succeed, they would just fuck up the finale.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8338383802933758622" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

