<div id="review_271620761" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/271620761" />
    <a title="Kirstine" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/5172557-kirstine"><img alt="Kirstine" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1505503603p2/5172557.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/271620761?book_show_action=true">Feb 03, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Kirstine" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Kirstine" href="/user/show/5172557-kirstine">Kirstine</a>
      </span>

          added it




        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5172557-kirstine?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5172557-kirstine?shelf=translated">translated</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer271620761" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4485161679741180353">If I had to rate this book from personal opinion, I would have given it 2 stars, but I&apos;m gonna go with three, because this book does exactly what it sets out to do: it&apos;s a proper slap in the face. It&apos;s a harsh, sometimes cruel, sometimes overwhelming, and always, sadly, a true portrayal of humanity right now. This book will make you face truths you&apos;d rather ignore, and that is why it deserves three stars, because so few books do that. And do it so well. That is the skill of Coehlo; he writes ext</span>
  <span id="freeText4485161679741180353" style="display:none">If I had to rate this book from personal opinion, I would have given it 2 stars, but I'm gonna go with three, because this book does exactly what it sets out to do: it's a proper slap in the face. It's a harsh, sometimes cruel, sometimes overwhelming, and always, sadly, a true portrayal of humanity right now. This book will make you face truths you'd rather ignore, and that is why it deserves three stars, because so few books do that. And do it so well. That is the skill of Coehlo; he writes extremely convincingly. <br /><br />Another review reads that this book inspires, it doesn't entertain, and that's perhaps the best description of it. This book sort of goes: "This is the worst of reality, this is the scum of humanity. Go do better. Go <em>be</em> better." And it will make you want to do just that, but you won't necessarily enjoy the ride to get there. <br /><br />My personal dislike for it mainly stems from the fact that this book isn't very hopeful, and I don't deal well with that. Utter misery, however real and relevant, always brings me down. Give me just a shred of hope and I'll forgive anything, but this book doesn't have that, at least not in my memory.<br /><br />In any case, if you want to read it, make sure you do it on a good day.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4485161679741180353" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


